  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Performing Hysteria,\" published by Leuven University Press in 2020, has yet to generate significant citations or online discourse, indicating a nascent footprint within both academic and public communities. However, it is available on commercial platforms like Amazon and Goodreads, suggesting potential accessibility for interested readers.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although \"Performing Hysteria\" has not yet attracted a notable number of citations, with only six recorded citations according to available data, its presence on commercial book platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads indicates a level of engagement from potential readers. This commercial linkage suggests that there may be an audience interested in the themes explored in the book, even if the scholarly impact remains in development.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The absence of significant community discussions or public discourse surrounding the work, as evidenced by its lack of mentions on platforms like Wikipedia, Reddit, and Bluesky, reflects the challenges it faces in gaining traction among both academic and broader public audiences. Without online conversations or mentions, the visibility of \"Performing Hysteria\" in the contemporary discourse about hysteria in performance studies remains limited.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Furthermore, the lack of high-fidelity social and community discourse points to an opportunity for further engagement and exploration within the field. The work's themes may resonate with those interested in performance studies and hysteria, but without a concerted effort to integrate it into broader discussions, its potential for influence may remain unfulfilled.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In summary, while \"Performing Hysteria\" is positioned within a commercial context that could facilitate readership, its academic engagement and community discourse are currently underutilized. Future efforts to highlight its contributions to performance studies and mental health narratives may foster a more vibrant discussion and increase its impact within both scholarly and public arenas.</p>",
